      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm looking at my student loan statement and the principal isn't going down as fast as i thought it would. i'm making my full payments every month but it feels like nothing is happening. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated each month and why it feels like the balance barely moves at first?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That is a very common feeling, but don't worry, your principal isn't actually stuck; it's just being held hostage by the interest, which is the most annoying thing about student loans. When you make your full payment, the bank first grabs a chunk of that money to pay off the interest that has been accruing since the last month, and only the *remainder* actually goes toward reducing your principal.\n\nThink of it like a tiny, invisible army of debt-eating goblins living inside your loan balance. Every single day, these goblins are eating away at your principal, and they are very hungry. If your monthly payment is exactly equal to how much the goblins are eating, then you will never see your principal go down at all, which is why it feels like nothing is happening.\n\nThe reason it feels like the balance barely moves at first is that the interest rate is usually calculated on the *entire* outstanding balance, which is huge when you first start. So, in the beginning, the goblins are devouring a massive amount of your payment, leaving almost nothing for the principal. As you pay down the balance over time, the goblins get smaller and smaller, and eventually, your payment starts to",
      "source": "target",
